ref=3D"https://www.statlect.com/probability-distributions/geometric-distrib=
ution#hid12">Solved exercises</a></p><ol><li><p><a href=3D"https://www.stat=
lect.com/probability-distributions/geometric-distribution#hid13">Exercise 1=
</a></p></li></ol></li></ol>
</div></div>


<h2 id=3D"hid2" class=3D"subsection">Intuition</h2>
<p>
   Consider a
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/probability-distributions/Bernoulli=
-distribution">Bernoulli
   experiment</a>, that is, a random experiment having two possible outcome=
s:
   either success or failure.
</p>
<p>
   We repeat the experiment until we get the first success, and then we cou=
nt the
   number
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2855px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   of failures that we faced prior to recording the success.
</p>
<p>
   Since the experiments are random,
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2806px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   is a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/ra=
ndom-variables">random
   variable</a>.
</p>
<p>
   If the repetitions of the experiment are
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/indepen=
dent-random-variables">independent</a>
   of each other, then the distribution of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"15" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$X,$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2492px;vertical=
-align:-5px"></span>
   is called geometric distribution.
</p>
<div class=3D"example">
   <p><span class=3D"titoletto">Example</span>
      If we toss a coin until we obtain head, the number of tails before th=
e first
      head has a geometric distribution.
   </p>
</div>
<p>
   At the end of this lecture we will also study a slight variant of the
   geometric distribution, called shifted geometric distribution. The latte=
r is
   the distribution of the total number of trials (all the failures + the f=
irst
   success).
</p>
<p>
   In other words, if
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2734px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   has a geometric distribution, then
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"38" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$X+1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2328px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   has a shifted geometric distribution.
</p>
<div class=3D"artContainer">
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"statlectArt" width=3D"780" heigh=
t=3D"195" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/geometric-distribution.png=
" alt=3D"Difference between the geometric distribution and its shifted vers=
ion."></span>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"hid3" class=3D"subsection">Definition</h2>
<p>
   The geometric distribution is characterized as follows.
</p>
<div class=3D"definition">
   <p><span class=3D"titoletto">Definition</span>
      Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2589px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
      be a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/discrete-random-va=
riable">discrete random
      variable</a>. Let
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"67" height=3D"26" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq1]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1978px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>.
      Let the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/support-of-a-ra=
ndom-variable">support</a> of
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2516px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
      be the set of non-negative
      integers<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"73" heig=
ht=3D"41" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAA=
LAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq2]" style=3D"background-position:0p=
x -1912px;"></span>We
      say that
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"25" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2830px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
      has a <strong>geometric distribution</strong> with
       <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/parameter">parameter</a=
>
      <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"26" src=
=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAA=
AICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"p" style=3D"background-position:0px -3067px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
      if its  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/probability-mass=
-function">probability mass
      function</a>
      is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"239" height=
=3D"81" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/geometric-distribution__12.p=
ng" alt=3D"[eq3]"></span>
   </p>
</div>
<p>
   The following is a proof that
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq4]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2303px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   is a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/le=
gitimate-probability-mass-function">legitimate probability mass function</a=
>.
</p>

<div class=3D"bproof"><span class=3D"bproof">Proof</span></div>
<div id=3D"idn1" class=3D"clps"><div class=3D"proofline">
<p>The probabilities
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq5]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2278px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   are well-defined and non-negative for any
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -3043px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   because
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"67" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq6]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2004px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>.
   We just need to prove that the sum of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"40" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq7]" style=3D"background-position:0px -2253px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   over its support equals
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"1" style=3D"background-position:0px -3019px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>:
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"139" height=3D"252"=
 src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABA=
AEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq8]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1161px=
;"></span>where
   in step
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$frame{A}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2458px;ve=
rtical-align:-8px"></span>
   we have used the
    <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_series">formula for
   geometric series</a>.</p></div></div>
<h2 id=3D"hid4" class=3D"subsection">Relation to the Bernoulli distribution=
</h2>
<p>
   Remember that a Bernoulli random variable is equal to:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"1" style=3D"background-position:0px -2998px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
         (success) with probability
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"p" style=3D"background-position:0px -2976px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"0" style=3D"background-position:0px -2955px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
         (failure) with probability
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"36" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$1-p$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2378px;v=
ertical-align:-5px"></span>.
      </p>
